<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gore Courts Black Support  </HEADLINE>
By LAWRENCE KNUTSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- With President Clinton at his side, Al Gore
summoned the black community to vote by the millions in November to
help extend the Democratic grip on the White House.
</P>
<P>
   ''I believe it's time to take the next step in civil rights,''
Gore told applauding members of the Congressional Black Caucus
Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   ''I believe it is time to end racial profiling in America,'' he
said. ''And that will be the first order of business of the
Gore-Lieberman administration.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore also promised to work for full voting rights for the
District of Columbia, which has a majority black population but,
under the Constitution, no voting representation in the U.S.
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Referring to the caucus by its three initials -- CBC -- Gore
launched a long litany in the style of civil rights activist Jesse
Jackson in admonishing the CBC members to vote and get out other
blacks to vote Democratic in the November election.
</P>
<P>
   ''For another administration that looks like America, vote
CBC,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   ''For an administration that keeps affirmative action going,
vote CBC.''
</P>
<P>
   He repeated the theme, touching more than a dozen issues,
including education, health and, repeatedly, the expansion of civil
rights for all Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ''With your help, I'm hoping to come back here next year in a
different capacity,'' the vice president said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Tonight, I came to listen and clap and say thanks,'' the
president said as he followed Gore to the podium. ''Thanks you for
giving me a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Thank you for standing with Al Gore and me in our simple and
profound mission to make sure that everyone in our country has a
chance,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   And the president said that when his own troubles mounted, he
took heart from the support he received from black officials in
general and the CBC in particular.
</P>
<P>
   ''Nothing that I have achieved would have been possible without
the Congressional Black Caucus,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's address highlighted a weekend rallying black support for
himself and his running mate, Sen. Joseph Lieberman of Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   A peppy, overflow crowd of 1,600 students at historically black
Howard University cheered him Friday morning. A standing-room-only
audience of black Clinton administration appointees provided
repeated chants of ''Go Al! Go Al!'' during his half-hour speech
Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   Political analysts say that Gore may be able to count on a high
percentage of the black vote in his race against George W. Bush.
But they say assuring a heavy black turnout is vital to his chances
-- especially in swing states like New Jersey, Missouri, Florida and
Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   Gore now has the support of about eight in 10 blacks,
solidifying support which dipped before the Democratic convention,
polls suggest.
</P>
<P>
   This coming week, Gore will head West to raise more money for
the Democratic National Committee, which has been financing the
bulk of Gore's TV ad war with Bush.
</P>
<P>
   The DNC began running a new ad Saturday featuring Gore talking
about education. The committee will spend $2 million to $3 million
over the next week airing the spot in 17 battleground states.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president had fund-raisers planned through the week,
including a Monday night event in Beverly Hills organized by
director Rob Reiner, a Tuesday fund-raiser in the San Francisco Bay
area, and a Saturday event in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   On the campaign trail, Gore plans to focus on health policy, an
area where he currently enjoys a clear advantage over Bush in
polls. This week, he plans to put a twist on his long-proposed
''bill of rights'' for HMO patients, promote proposals to seal the
privacy of medical records, and hold a rally around his plan to
give seniors a Medicare benefit for prescription drugs.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the week, Gore will head home to Washington for
preparations for the first of three presidential debates on Oct. 3.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
