<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-17 00:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia 3, Yugoslavia 1  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia (AP) -- Riding the high-velocity serves of
Roman Yakovlev, Russia rallied from an early deficit to defeat
Yugoslavia 3-1 in a close battle between two of the world's best
teams.
</P>
<P>
   Yakovlev, whose stutter-step approach produces a wicked 75-mph
jump serve, led the Russians to a 19-25, 25-23, 25-23, 25-20
victory Sunday (Saturday night EDT).
</P>
<P>
   Russia, ranked second in the world, is trying to regain the
prestige it lost in the 1990s. After winning three golds and two
silvers in their first six Olympics, the Russians finished seventh
in 1992 and fourth in '96.
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslavia, which came out of nowhere to win the Olympic bronze
in 1996, is ranked sixth, but also a strong contender for the gold.
</P>
<P>
   Russia lost seven of the last nine points to drop the first
game, then stormed back behind Yakovlev. A clean ace broke a 23-23
tie, and Iakovlev won the set with another serve the Yugoslavs
barely got a hand on.
</P>
<P>
   The teams matched each other shot for shot in the third set, and
once again it was tied at 23. A smash by Russian Sergei Tetioukhin
over 6-foot-7 blocker Igor Vusurovic made it 24-23, and Igor
Choulepov got the winner on another shot past Vusurovic.
</P>
<P>
   The Russians jumped to a 7-1 lead in the fourth game and didn't
look back. Yakovlev finished with five aces.
</P>
</TEXT>
