<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-17 01:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fujimori Calls New Elections  </HEADLINE>
By MONTE HAYES
<TEXT>
<P>
   LIMA, Peru (AP) -- President Alberto Fujimori, besieged by a
bribery scandal surrounding a top aide, announced Saturday that he
was calling new elections and that he would not be a candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Immediately after the announcement on national television,
thousands of people gathered outside the presidential palace in
Lima, chanting anti-Fujimori slogans and demanding the
authoritarian president who has ruled this country since 1990 leave
office.
</P>
<P>
   In other parts of Lima and cities in Peru's interior, caravans
of drivers waved Peruvian flags and honked their car horns late
into the night, celebrating the news.
</P>
<P>
   The 62-year-old Fujimori, smiling and looking at ease, did not
announce a date for the new elections, but said they were necessary
after the political uproar over a videotape allegedly showing his
intelligence chief bribing an opposition congressman to support the
government.
</P>
<P>
   Fujimori said he would ''deactivate'' the National Intelligence
Service, headed by the feared Vladimiro Montesinos, a close
Fujimori adviser at the center of the bribery scandal. Fujimori did
not elaborate what steps he would take with the agency.
</P>
<P>
   ''After a profound reflection, and an objective evaluation of
the circumstances, I have made the decision, first, to deactivate
the system of national intelligence and, in second place, call in
the quickest time possible general elections,'' Fujimori said in
the eight-minute address.
</P>
<P>
   ''In these general elections, it's obvious he who is speaking
will not participate,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Fujimori was elected to an unprecedented third five-year term in
voting that ended with a second round in May. His opponent in the
runoff dropped out because of allegations of vote-fixing and
Fujimori's victory brought heavy criticism from the United States
and other nations.
</P>
<P>
   He had been working to repair his international reputation when
the video was released Thursday showing what appeared to be
Montesinos offering a wad of cash to opposition congressman Alberto
Kouri for his support of the government.
</P>
<P>
   The scandal fueled calls for a new election by leaders of the
opposition, who since the election have accused Fujimori's
government of systematically offering opposition legislators cash
to join their ranks.
</P>
<P>
   Fujimori said that once the video was released, his position was
''to support a severe investigation to determine responsibilities
before the law.''
</P>
<P>
   ''This above all is a political development which obviously has
had a strong impact on the stability of my government and of the
country,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Hours before Fujimori's announcement, the Organization of
American States issued a strongly worded demand that he suspend
Montesinos and other officials allegedly linked to the scandal,
warning that otherwise attempts at reconciliation with the
opposition would be damaged.
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, Montesinos has been accused of illicit
enrichment and engineering smear campaigns against Fujimori's
opponents in this year's presidential elections.
</P>
<P>
   A leading opposition congressman, Henry Pease, questioned
whether Fujimori could carry out his promise and said that it could
be that Montesinos, long considered the power behind the
government, would stay and Fujimori go. Pease also expressed
concern over the lack of a timetable for elections.
</P>
<P>
   Congressman Luis Solari, a supporter of Alejandro Toledo, who
pulled out of the May presidential runoff charging Fujimori with
planning to rig the results, praised Fujimori for his decision.
</P>
<P>
   As hundreds of anti-Fujimori protesters crowded around him in
the Plaza de Armas in front of the palace, Solari said, ''It's a
victory for the forgotten of Peru.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-17-00 0113 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
