<HEADLINE> US Team Chases Aussies in Three-Day  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia (AP) -- Australia is having little trouble
dominating equestrian at the Sydney Olympics, although the United
States got closer Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The second day of the dressage phase of the team three-day event
saw Karen O'Connor of Middleburg, Va., boost the American position
to third place with a personal best of 32.6 on Prince Panache. It
was the third-lowest score of the two days of dressage.
</P>
<P>
   ''Timing is everything,'' she said. ''He's been training great
for the last three weeks, going from strength to strength.''
</P>
<P>
   The Aussies are traditionally weak in dressage and dominant in
the jumping phases, so they're in a strong position to add a Sydney
gold to the ones they won in Barcelona and Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Australia takes 112.6 penalty points into the demanding
cross-country phase Monday, with stadium jumping to follow on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Stuart Tinney added 36.0 points on Jeepster for Australia, while
Andrew Hoy had a leading 30.6 on Darien Powers.
</P>
<P>
   The hosts are followed closely by Britain with 115.2 and the
United States with 125.4. Britain's Pippa Funnell had the
second-best score Sunday of 32.0 on Supreme Rock. The top three
scores from each team's four riders count for the total.
</P>
<P>
   Linden Wiesman of Bluemont, Va., was delighted with her score of
48.4 on Anderoo, which was added to David O'Connor's 44.4 on
Giltedge from Saturday. David and Karen O'Connor are married and
veterans of the silver-medal team in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ''I hoped, maybe on a good day, we'd break 50,'' Wiesman said.
''It was amazing cantering into that ring.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
