<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Volleyball: Netherlands 3, Cuba 0  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia (AP) -- Towering blockers Martin van der Horst
and Bas van der Goor led the Netherlands to a surprisingly easy 3-0
victory over high-flying Cuba in the first round of Olympic men's
volleyball.
</P>
<P>
   The Dutch began their longshot quest to repeat as gold-medal
champions with a 25-23, 25-20, 25-23 victory Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The Dutch aren't nearly as powerful as they were four years ago,
having barely qualified for the 12-team field. But their ball
control, and the net play of the 7-foot van der Horst and 6-10 van
der Goor, were too much for the Cubans.
</P>
<P>
   Cuba's graceful leapers are famous for playing some of the most
exciting volleyball in the world, but they're also known for their
mistakes. Two of the Netherlands' final three points came on Cuban
net violations.
</P>
<P>
   The first game was tied at 22 when the Dutch took control. An
ace by van der Goor made it 23-22, and after van der Horst and
Reinder Nummerdor stopped cold a spike from Cuba's 6-11 Osvaldo
Hernandez, van der Goor served out the set with another ace.
</P>
<P>
   The second game also was close, but the Netherlands pulled away
from a 20-19 lead by taking five of the next six points.
</P>
<P>
   Dutch hitter Richard Schuil had 18 kills in just 29 attempts.
Cuba's Angel Denis, a 6-4 player with a spectacular vertical leap,
had 12 kills in 30 tries.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
