<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Olympic Basketball Roundup  </HEADLINE>
By JIM O'CONNELL
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia (AP) -- The pile of bodies at midcourt looked
like the end of an NCAA tournament first-round game.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday (Saturday night EDT), players from Italy, not
Valparaiso, were jumping on each other, and it was the Olympics,
not March Madness.
</P>
<P>
   Andrea Meneghin's 3-pointer with 25 seconds to play -- his only
points of the game -- gave Italy a 50-48 victory over Lithuania. The
celebration that followed capped a tense, possession-by-possession
game between the teams most consider the second and third best in
Group A behind the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ''The first game is always the most important. That's why we're
so happy,'' said Italy's Carlton Myers, who had nine points in a
foul-plagued 22 minutes. ''It was very tense, close and ugly, but
at the end we won it and that's what's important.''
</P>
<P>
   Meneghin, the son of Dino Meneghin who is considered the
greatest player in Italy's history and is an assistant coach, had
missed all six shots he had taken, including two 3-pointers in the
previous 45 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   But he made the one that counted. And when Lithuania misfired on
two 3-point shots in the final 12 seconds, Italy won its first
Olympic game since 1984 when Dino Meneghin was the star of the
team.
</P>
<P>
   ''It came down to one shot and they made it and we didn't,''
said Lithuania's Mindaugas Timinskas, who played at Iona College.
</P>
<P>
   Timinskas' driving layup with 41 seconds left gave Lithuania a
48-47 lead and were his only points of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ''I can't believe we scored 50 points. There were no easy
baskets,'' Italy coach Bogdan Tanjevic said. ''I didn't think we
played that well but we were fortunate and it was a game of good
defense.''
</P>
<P>
   Italy finished with a better shooting percentage, 32.6
(15-for-46), as Lithuania managed a 13-for-50 effort (26 percent).
</P>
<P>
   ''The shooting hurt us but maybe it was also the Italian
defense,'' Lithuania coach Jonas Kazlauskas said.
</P>
<P>
France 76, New Zealand 50
</P>
<P>
   France, making its first appearance in men's Olympic basketball
since 1984, used its speed advantage to pull away.
</P>
<P>
   Yann Bonato and Cyril Julian each had had eight points in a 26-4
run that gave France a 35-19 lead with 2:32 left in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   France held New Zealand to one field goal over that stretch as
it overcame a six-point deficit and went on to a 38-23 lead. France
then scored the first nine points of the second half and the rout
was on.
</P>
<P>
   Bonato finished with 16 points for France, which hadn't been in
the basketball competition for 24 years before competing in Los
Angeles and finishing 11th.
</P>
<P>
   Sean Marks, who played at the University of California and for
the NBA's Toronto Raptors, had 12 points to lead New Zealand, which
was making its first appearance in the basketball competition.
</P>
<P>
Yugoslavia 66, Russia 60
</P>
<P>
   Zeljko Rebraca scored 18 points and fellow center Dejean
Tomasevic added 13 as Yugoslavia took advantage of Russian center
Sergei Panov's foul trouble in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's last lead was 36-34 with 15:48 to play and that's when
Panov went to the bench with his third foul. Rebraca and Tomasevic
then combined for 10 points in a 12-2 run that gave Yugoslavia the
lead for good.
</P>
<P>
   Panov, who finished with 13 points, fouled out with 5:08 to play
and Russia trailing 58-48 and it never got closer than six points
the rest of the way.
</P>
<P>
   Predrag Danilovic, who played for the Miami Heat, added 14
points Yugoslavia, which won the silver medal in the 1996 games and
has won a medal in the last five Olympics in which it has competed.
</P>
<P>
   ''We can play much, much, much better than we did today and we
will show that,'' Danilovic said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
