<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Seles, Davenport at Olympic Village  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia (AP) -- The athletes' village at the Sydney
Games had two new residents Sunday with lots of tennis rackets and
12 Grand Slam titles between them.
</P>
<P>
   Lindsay Davenport, the defending Olympic women's singles
champion, and Monica Seles, the four-time Australian Open winner,
are rooming together at the village after checking out of a Sydney
hotel on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Olympic Committee said the tennis stars wanted to savor
the ''Olympic experience'' by living with more than 6,000 other
athletes in the compound of apartments just across the street from
Olympic Park, where the tennis tournament will be held beginning
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ''They are like kids at camp,'' said Sandy Baldwin, a USOC vice
president and mission chief for the U.S. team in the village.
</P>
<P>
   Because the village is crowded with a record number of athletes,
Baldwin had to move, too, to make room for the new residents. She
left her apartment, where she was living solo, to share space with
three other U.S. team administrators.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
