<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beach Volleyball: Canada Beats U.S.  </HEADLINE>
By TOM COHEN
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia (AP) -- Americans Rob Heidger and Kevin Wong
lost a five-point lead and failed to convert a half-dozen match
points Sunday, losing 17-15 to Canadians Jody Holden and Conrad
Leinemann in Olympic men's beach volleyball.
</P>
<P>
   The loss by Heidger and Wong on the first day of the men's
competition Sunday followed victories by both U.S. women's teams in
their opening matches the day before.
</P>
<P>
   The other U.S. men's team of Dain Blanton and Eric Fonoimoana
was playing later Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Heidger and Wong started strongly, jumping to leads of 5-1 and
7-3 before Canada, on strong serving by Holden and Leinemann that
included two aces on the back line, scored six straight points for
a 9-7 lead.
</P>
<P>
   American supporters started a ''USA'' chant, and Heidger and
Wong came back with five points of their own for a 12-9 lead after
35 minutes of play that had the sellout afternoon crowd roaring.
</P>
<P>
   Heidger then scored points on successive blocks of Leinemann to
make it 14-9 before the Canadians mounted their own comeback, with
Holden firing serves in excess of 50 mph to set up two straight
kills by Leinemann off the U.S. returns.
</P>
<P>
   Then it was Leinemann's turn, serving for two more points to
make it 14-13. Heidger and Wong called time out as the crowd full
of flags and costumed spectators danced and chanted.
</P>
<P>
   Holden's fault tied it 14-14, but Heidger then blocked Leinemann
for a one-point U.S. lead before Wong put the next serve. The
Canadians, with the serve back, scored for 15-15.
</P>
<P>
   Leinemann provided defensive heroics late, running down balls to
keep rallies going and then lobbing a deep kill to give Canada the
lead at 16-15. His block of Heidger ended the game that lasted more
than an hour.
</P>
<P>
   The Canadians hugged each other as the audience cheered the most
entertaining match so far.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, Juan Ibarra and Joel Sotelo of Mexico pulled off the
first major upset by outlasting the top-seeded Australians Julien
Prosser and Lee Zahner, 15-12.
</P>
<P>
   The victory was the first in four matches for the Mexican pair
over Prosser and Zahner, and advanced the last-seeded team into the
final 16 of the men's competition, while sending Prosser and Zahner
to the loser's bracket.
</P>
<P>
   Ibarra provided strong defense, constantly digging out kill
attempts by the Australians and setting up Sotelo for lobs and
smashes that kept the top seeds off balance.
</P>
<P>
   The Mexicans trailed only twice, at 3-2 and 12-11, and scored
the final four points, with Ibarra's dig of a smash by Zahner
ricocheting back off the top of the net and falling between the
Australians to finish the match.
</P>
<P>
   That set off a celebration for the Mexicans and a small,
flag-waving contingent of their fans, while Prosser and Zahner
slumped in disbelief.
</P>
<P>
   ''It wasn't good, that's all I know,'' Zahner said. ''It's going
to take a few hours to get over it. Right now it's pretty
devastating.''
</P>
<P>
   In other morning matches, the fourth-seeded Swiss brothers Paul
and Martin Laciga held on for a 15-13 victory over the Czech duo of
Michal Palinek and Martin Lebl, and fifth-seeded Eduardo Esteban
Martinez and Martin Conde of Argentina defeated the Italian team of
Andrea Raffaelli and Maurizio Pimponi, 15-7.
</P>
<P>
   Defending bronze medalists John Child and Mark Heese of Canada,
the sixth seeds, cruised to a 15-5 triumph over the 19th-ranked
French duo of Jean Philippe Jodard and Christian Penigaud.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's Sergey Ermishin and Mikhail Kouchnerev beat Mariano
Baracetti and Jose Salema of Argentina, 15-4, and Luis Maia and
Joao Brenha of Portugal topped Jan Kvalheim and Bjorn Maaseide of
Norway 15-10.
</P>
<P>
   In a mild upset, Jorg Ahmann and Axel Hager of Germany beat
10th-seeded Javier Bosma and Fabio Diez of Spain 15-13, and
Norway's Joerre Kjemperud and Vegard Hoidalen won over Nikolas
Berger and Oliver Stamm of Austria by 15-6.
</P>
<P>
   The winners advance to the final 16 and get four days off while
the losers enter elimination play to try to remain in contention
for a medal.
</P>
<P>
   Martin Laciga leveled the first complaint about the Bondi Beach
court, which had been widely praised by players as a top quality
facility on the picturesque beach. The sand in the stadium was
deeper than on the practice courts and required getting used to,
Laciga said.
</P>
<P>
   ''You practice on the side courts and then you go to the center
court and it's different,'' he said. ''No one told you about it and
that's not right.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-17-00 0201 </TRAILER>
