<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-17 02:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dragneva Wins Gold in Weightlifting  </HEADLINE>
By ALAN ROBINSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia (AP) -- Tara Nott, who tried two other sports
before settling on weightlifting only four years ago, won a
surprise silver medal for the United States as women's
weightlifting made its Olympic debut Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Nott, never higher than ninth in the world championships, placed
second to gold medalist Izabela Dragneva of Bulgaria at 106 pounds.
Raema Lisa Rumbewas of Indonesia took the bronze.
</P>
<P>
   Dragneva had the best lifts in both the snatch (187&AMP;frac14; pounds) and
the clean and jerk (231&AMP;frac14; pounds) to finish with a total lift of
418&AMP;frac34; pounds. Nott's total was 407&AMP;frac34; pounds, 181&AMP;frac34; pounds in
the
snatch and 225&AMP;frac34; pounds in the clean and jerk.
</P>
<P>
   Rumbewas, who missed a final lift of 236&AMP;frac34; pounds that would have
moved her past Nott, also had a total of 407&AMP;frac34; pounds, but was
placed lower because she weighed slightly more than Nott.
</P>
<P>
   Nott also missed her final lift in the clean and jerk, at 231&AMP;frac14;
pounds, but it would not have been enough to overtake Dragneva,
normally the No. 2 lifter on Bulgaria's team.
</P>
<P>
   Nott got a big break when Donka Mincheva, the reigning world
champion and world record holder from Bulgeria, bombed out by
missing all three lifts in the snatch. A lifter must make at least
one successful lift in the snatch, raising the bar above the head
in one fluid motion, before advancing to the clean and jerk, where
the bar is raised to the collarbone and then overhead.
</P>
<P>
   Mincheva, who had an appendectomy about a month ago, did not
look strong or especially confident and didn't come close on three
lifts, two at 176&AMP;frac14; pounds and one at 181&AMP;frac34; pounds.
</P>
<P>
   It took Nott several years to do so, but she finally settled
into weightlifting after first trying gymnastics and soccer. Now
28, she is the only athlete to have trained at the U.S. Olympic
Training Center in Colorado Springs in three sports.
</P>
<P>
   After playing on the U.S. under-21 and under-23 soccer teams,
she landed a desk job at the Atlanta Games helping soccer players.
There, she met several weightlifting coaches who, noticing her
strength and compact size, encouraged her to switch sports.
</P>
<P>
   In less than a year, the Colorado College graduate who grew up
in Stilwell, Kansas, trying to outdo her three male cousins in
virtually every sport, was a national champion.
</P>
<P>
   She has won national titles in the lowest weight class every
year since except 1998, when an injury contributed to a bronze
finish. She was the only female lifter to make all six of her lifts
in the U.S. Olympic trials in suburban New Orleans in July.
</P>
<P>
   Robin Goad, considered the grand dame of American women's
weightlifting after 18 years in the sport, couldn't match her U.S.
trials lift of 176&AMP;frac14; pounds in the snatch. She missed two of three
lifts, converting only at 170&AMP;frac34; pounds, and wound up with a total
lift of 391&AMP;frac14; pounds for sixth.
</P>
<P>
   Goad was pregnant upon learning in 1996 that women's
weightlifting would be an Olympic sport in 2000. After giving birth
to a daughter that she and weight-lifting husband Dean Goad named
Sydney, she immediately came out of retirement and resumed
training.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-17-00 0202 </TRAILER>
