<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-17 02:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New York Mayor Marches in Parade  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- A day after undergoing major treatment for
prostate cancer, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani on Saturday marched two
dozen blocks in a Manhattan parade.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor appeared to be operating at full force, stepping off
at noon in the German-American Steuben Parade up Fifth Avenue.
Wearing a cap inscribed ''Mount Sinai'' -- the hospital where he
underwent the procedure Friday -- Giuliani said the doctors ''did it
in such a skillful way that I'm able to march.''
</P>
<P>
   At the start of the parade, Senate candidate Rep. Rick Lazio and
Yankees owner George Steinbrenner greeted Giuliani with hugs.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor proceeded up Fifth with Lazio and Steinbrenner,
followed by Judith Nathan, a woman Giuliani has called his ''very
good friend.''
</P>
<P>
   At the parade's end, the mayor held a news conference -- as he
had done Friday, barely five hours after radioactive seeds were
implanted in his cancerous prostate. His doctors said Friday the
treatment went ''perfectly'' and called the mayor's prognosis
''excellent.''
</P>
<P>
   After Saturday's parade, Giuliani dove into the crowd on the
sidewalk, shaking hands and chatting before ducking into a
drugstore.
</P>
<P>
   Then, accompanied by a handful of people, including Nathan, he
walked toward Gracie Mansion, greeting surprised passersby.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
