<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-17 02:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Myanmar Paper Denounces Opposition  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   YANGON, Myanmar (AP) -- Myanmar's democratic opposition party
should be eliminated before its leader Aung San Suu Kyi becomes
more daring and causes more suffering to the nation, an editorial
in an official newspaper said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Opinions in the official press reflect those of the military
government in Myanmar, and the commentary underscored rising
tensions between the regime and its political opponents, amid
rumors the government plans to close the party down by the year's
end.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, Suu Kyi's National League for Democracy held its
first meeting since a two-week crackdown against the party, and
declared it would draft a national constitution in defiance of the
military government.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is almost no political party in Myanmar history which is
as mean and evil as the NLD'' and Suu Kyi, said an editorial in the
Myanma Ahlin newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   ''The government has tolerated the NLD for so many years but it
is time the party be completely eliminated,'' it said.
</P>
<P>
   The commentary was written by Hla Soe, a disaffected former NLD
member. He was elected as a parliamentary representative for the
party in 1990 general elections that were swept by the NLD, which
was never allowed to take power.
</P>
<P>
   Nine party leaders including Suu Kyi, winner of the 1991 Nobel
Peace Prize for her peaceful struggle for democracy in Myanmar --
also known as Burma -- were confined to their homes for two weeks in
late August after Suu Kyi tried to travel outside Yangon on party
work.
</P>
<P>
   Then on Sept. 1, Suu Kyi was forcibly brought back to the
capital Yangon after a nine-day stand-off in which she and other
party members camped by their vehicles after authorities prevented
them from traveling to the provinces to do party work.
</P>
<P>
   Yangon's crackdown drew vehement international criticism, mainly
from the United States and Britain, which accused the regime of
blatantly violating the Myanmar opposition leaders' political
rights. Myanmar accused both countries of meddling in its internal
affairs.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is time the government takes care of the problem according
to the law,'' Hla Soe wrote. ''If the problem is taken lightly the
Americans, British and Daw Suu Kyi will become more daring and the
country will suffer more.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
