<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Anti-Smoking Appearance for Chelsea  </HEADLINE>
By JOSEPH WHITE
<TEXT>
<P>
   RICHMOND, Australia (AP) -- Chelsea Clinton is a private citizen,
Donna Shalala is a U.S. Cabinet minister. Guess which one drew the
crowd?
</P>
<P>
   The president's daughter stepped out of her car and was quickly
surrounded by Australian children and their parents at an
appearance Sunday to promote a smoking prevention initiative aimed
at Australian girls.
</P>
<P>
   ''I had a good time in Sydney,'' Chelsea said as she autographed
soccer balls and even a boy's green soccer jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Later, at the end of a press conference in this Melbourne
suburb, Chelsea did a first on her Olympics trip: she answered a
reporter's question.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've never smoked a cigarette in my life,'' she said when
asked if she had a smoking history.
</P>
<P>
   Shalala, the secretary of Health and Human Services, launched
the campaign along with Australian health minister Michael
Wooldridge and a member of the Australian women's soccer team.
</P>
<P>
   The program is similar to one launched with the U.S. women's
soccer team four years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm pleased to be here as Australia joins the team -- helping
us to reach young girls from Melbourne to Milan to Milwaukee,''
Shalala said.
</P>
<P>
   Even Shalala's speech got upstaged by Chelsea. A young girl in a
blue dress, pacifier in her mouth, walked to Chelsea's chair during
the speech. Chelsea leaned forward and stroked the girl's blonde
hair as the cameras flashed.
</P>
<P>
   Chelsea, Shalala and the rest of the U.S, government delegation
attended swimming events Saturday night in Sydney before flying to
Melbourne Sunday morning.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. delegation was in Melbourne to watch the U.S.-China
women's soccer game that evening.
</P>
<P>
   Rushed to get to the game on time, Chelsea turned over her
autograph signing session to Australian soccer player Amy Taylor,
who signed the new posters coinciding with the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ''If we can teach the kids when they're young the do's and
don't's, they've got a better chance,'' Taylor said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
