<HEADLINE> Battle Over Italian Author's Estate  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME (AP) -- A long-running battle over the estate of Giorgio
Bassani, author of ''The Garden of the Finzi-Continis,'' took
another ugly turn over the weekend when police raided his
companion's hotel room.
</P>
<P>
   They hauled off several carloads of paintings, manuscripts,
silver and other valuables, Italian newspapers reported Sunday.
They said the valuables were worth millions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Bassani, renowned for his semi-autobiographical novel about
Italian Jews during the rise of Fascism, died in April at age 84.
He suffered from Parkinson's and Alzheimer's disease.
</P>
<P>
   His later years were marked by bitter court battles between his
family, which tried to have him declared incompetent to manage his
financial affairs, and Bassani's longtime companion, Portia Prebys,
an American-born professor of comparative literature.
</P>
<P>
   Bassani was long separated from his wife, Valeria Sinigallia,
with whom he had two children.
</P>
<P>
   Italian newspapers said that police, acting on a complaint from
Bassani's wife and children, on Saturday raided the Hotel Tiziano
in central Rome where Prebys had been living since the writer's
death.
</P>
<P>
   Police confiscated valuables -- including paintings, silver,
jewelry and manuscripts -- which allegedly were from the Rome
apartment Prebys and Bassani had shared.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Garden of the Finzi-Continis,'' first published in 1962,
was widely translated and made into an Academy Award-winning movie
by director Vittorio De Sica in 1971.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
