<HEADLINE> Sri Lankan Military Captures Town  </HEADLINE>
By NAMINI WIJEDASA
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) -- Sri Lankan soldiers captured a
strategic northern town from Tamil Tiger rebels Sunday in a fresh
offensive backed by artillery and newly acquired Russian MiG-27
warplanes, an army spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   Four soldiers, including one officer, died and 46 were injured.
There were no immediate reports of rebel casualties and no comment
from the Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam.
</P>
<P>
   ''I can confirm that we have finished the operation and that we
took over the town of Chavakachcheri,'' said Brig. Sanath
Karunaratne.
</P>
<P>
   The capture of Chavakachcheri, nearly six miles east of Jaffna
city, is seen as a major victory for the government ahead of Oct.
10 parliamentary elections. Military gains against the rebels could
win votes for the ruling People's Alliance.
</P>
<P>
   The rebels wrested Chavakachcheri from the military after a
major offensive in May.
</P>
<P>
   Government spokesman Ariya Rubasinghe said government troops
have seen the Tamil rebels deserting their bases and defense lines.
</P>
<P>
   The rebels have been fighting a 17-year civil war for a separate
Tamil homeland in the north and east since 1983. More than 62,400
people have been killed in the conflict.
</P>
<P>
   The rebels accuse the majority Sinhalese, who control the
government and the military, of widespread discrimination against
the minority Tamils in education and jobs. The government denies
the charge.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's military operation was the government's third attack
this month. Last weekend, troops consolidated their hold on the
northern territory wrested from the rebels.
</P>
<P>
   Backed by MiG-27 warplanes, government troops destroyed 14 rebel
bunkers close to Jaffna on Sept. 10, killing 70 guerrillas and 17
soldiers. The operation succeeded in clearing the guerillas from
positions five to 10 miles east of Jaffna. The rebels hope to
reclaim Jaffna, a former guerrilla stronghold.
</P>
<P>
   There has been no comment by the rebels on the new attacks, but
a government statement released Saturday said the rebels have
admitted losing 392 fighters since the latest military operations
began Sept. 3.
</P>
<P>
   The government wants to dislodge the rebels from positions close
to Jaffna ahead of the elections to prevent possible guerrilla
attacks during voting in the area.
</P>
<P>
   Independent verification of the reports is not possible as both
sides don't allow reporters into the battle zone.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
