<BODY>
<HEADLINE> School board and union at odds over contract, and now, over a poll  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) - As Buffalo teachers prepare to head back to
classes for at least some of this week, a poll shows 57 percent of
county residents think they should not strike again.
</P>
<P>
   While 59 percent of Erie County residents say Buffalo teachers
have legitimate complaints, only 33 percent think walking out is
necessary, according to poll conducted by Zogby International for
Sunday's Buffalo News.
</P>
<P>
   The teachers union and school board offered different
interpretations of the survey.
</P>
<P>
   ''While we're not going to make our decisions on poll results,
it is comforting to know that almost two-thirds of the community
supports our belief that the strike shouldn't occur,'' said Paul
Buchanan, school board president.
</P>
<P>
   It was a view seconded by one of the state's top education
officials.
</P>
<P>
   ''Isn't it ironic that with this strike in Buffalo we have the
appalling example of calculated lawlessness on the part of the very
people we rely on to bring to our children the message of respect
for the law and our legal institutions?'' said Regents Chancellor
Carl T. Hayden, an Elmira attorney.
</P>
<P>
   Philip Rumore, president of the Buffalo Teachers Federation,
said he was surprised and gratified by the results. ''It's very
unusual to have that many people support a public employee
strike,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Pollster John Zogby had much the same impression.
</P>
<P>
   The results suggest that the recent strikes are ''not such a bad
move as one would expect,'' Zogby said. ''There is public sympathy,
but perhaps they have found the only tool available to focus that
public sympathy.''
</P>
<P>
   The Buffalo Teachers Federation's 3,700 teachers walked out for
two days earlier this month and unexpectedly resumed the strike
Thursday, canceling classes for 47,000 students. Under a judge's
order, they returned Friday and promised to stay there until the
state's mediator releases a proposal on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   In the countywide survey, 29 percent thought the teachers had no
reason to complain. The remaining 12 percent were undecided in the
poll conducted Thursday and Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The poll of 400 registered voters was conducted Thursday and
Friday and has a margin of error of plus or minus 5 percentage
points.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
