<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-17 13:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> BC-CT--Catholic Worker, Conn Bjt,950  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN CHRISTOFFERSEN
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) - Chris Doucot isn't sure how many times
he's been arrested for civil disobedience.
</P>
<P>
   ''I lost track. Forty or so,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the arrests stand out, like the time several years ago
when Doucot and his elderly mother-in-law chained shut the doors of
the federal building in downtown Hartford. At another protest he
spilled his blood on the building's pillars to symbolize the blood
spilled in wars.
</P>
<P>
   ''It took them a while to get it off,'' Doucot said, smiling
slightly as he carried a sign at a weekly protest at the federal
building against American support for sanctions against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   Doucot, 32, has fasted for up to 30 days to protest the Iraqi
sanctions. A junkie pistol-whipped him last year while Doucot was
giving food to the poor.
</P>
<P>
   Such is the life of a Catholic Worker. The radical movement was
started during the Depression by Dorothy Day, a Roman Catholic
convert and journalist, and Peter Maurin, a French peasant.
</P>
<P>
   Many groups help the poor. Catholic Workers actually live, in
voluntary poverty, among the poor. That, they say, helps them
understand the poor.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's what we believe we're called to do as Catholics,'' Doucot
said, recalling the Biblical story in which Jesus tells a rich man
to give up his wealth and follow him. ''We're trying to do our best
to not just believe in Jesus but to try and practice that with our
daily lives.''
</P>
<P>
   The Catholic Worker movement has more than 100 homes across the
country and abroad where they take in the homeless and others in
need. The homes are located in poor areas and some provide food,
furniture and other services. Nonviolent protests are a way of
life.
</P>
<P>
   In Connecticut, the Catholic Worker has houses in Hartford, New
Haven and Bridgeport and runs programs around the state.
</P>
<P>
   The Bridgeport house opened a year ago in a Spanish-speaking
neighborhood. Its main work so far involves coordinating a program
that brings high school and college students from surrounding towns
to Bridgeport to break down barriers.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-year-old New Haven house takes people in, offers meals and
engages in protests. A prayer circle is held in an area known for
drug dealing.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've come to the conclusion the service we do is a
privilege,'' says Mark Colville, a Catholic Worker in New Haven.
</P>
<P>
   Colville, who has a wife and two children, recently spent a year
in jail for participating in a protest in Maine in which blood was
spilled on a battleship.
</P>
<P>
   The Hartford Catholic Worker home is formally known as St.
Martin De Porres House. Neighbors call it ''the purple house''
because of its bright paint.
</P>
<P>
   The Hartford house has taken in prisoners, the poor and the
pregnant. A current resident, an 18-year-old woman, came from an
abused home and now is able to attend college because of the
Catholic Worker.
</P>
<P>
   Doucot and his wife, Jackie Allen, who have two young boys,
opened the house seven years ago. Some neighbors were skeptical at
first.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's a white family moving in the middle of the city,''
said D. McNeil, who lives next door. ''They found that unusual.''
</P>
<P>
   But the neighbors gradually came to accept the Catholic Worker
as they watched the group provide arts and crafts, summer camp and
other services for children. McNeil sends her niece to the house
and says she could talk for months about the good works done there.
</P>
<P>
   ''Chris and Jackie are wonderful people,'' McNeil said. ''They
do a great job working with the kids in the community - lots of
patience, very caring.''
</P>
<P>
   Children come by the purple house after school. A small boy
dressed in a polo shirt stands quietly outside the front of the
house, next to a black, wrought-iron fence where donated clothing
hangs for the taking.
</P>
<P>
   ''Hello Rodney,'' Doucot calls out. ''Do you want to come in the
backyard?''
</P>
<P>
   Rodney walks through the house and is soon playing on a swing,
smiling.
</P>
<P>
   A group of children arrive, but they are leery of an old dog in
the house. One child asks if the dog bites.
</P>
<P>
   ''Only if you bite him,'' Doucot says.
</P>
<P>
   The children come into the house and Doucot hands each of them
two pencils.
</P>
<P>
   ''I get this stuff for free?'' a boy asks, bewildered.
</P>
<P>
   ''Yeah, why not?'' Doucot replies.
</P>
<P>
   Doucot gives a girl a box of crayons, but she tries to give them
back.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't use crayons,'' the girl explains. ''I'm a
third-grader.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the children, Julio Rodriguez, 12, is asked what he
thinks of the people in the purple house.
</P>
<P>
   ''They're blessed,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   More and more children come by the house, and soon the backyard
playground is filled. Doucot prepares Kool-aid, while a woman who
calls herself Princess Di brings over snacks for the children.
</P>
<P>
   In another room, Doucot's son is watching Brian Kavanagh paint a
sign for a military protest planned the following day. A colorful
''Happy Birthday'' sign hangs on the wall for Brian, who just
turned 57.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, Kavanagh and Doucot quietly handed out
fliers at the federal building. Doucot, who says he has seen babies
who died because of the Gulf War-era sanctions against Iraq, holds
a sign contending that the sanctions have killed 600,000 Iraqi
children in the past decade.
</P>
<P>
   Most people ignore the protests. Others do not.
</P>
<P>
   ''Let them all die,'' a woman once told Kavanagh.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the response, the Catholic Workers have protested every
Friday for years. And while poverty may be the antithesis of the
American dream, the Catholic Workers find fulfillment.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm convinced I'm doing what God wants me to do in the place
God wants me to be,'' said the soft-spoken Kavanagh. ''I don't know
how many people can say that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
