<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Girl dies from E. Coli infection  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   MONTVILLE, Conn. (AP) - Lauren Mansel was an honor student and
athlete who was looking forward to starting the seventh grade.
</P>
<P>
   But the 12-year-old Montville girl became the third person in
Connecticut this year to die from an E. coli infection when she
passed away Thursday at Connecticut Children's Medical Center in
Hartford.
</P>
<P>
   Lauren, who was to attend Leonard Tyl Middle School, was a
member of the school's track and soccer teams, an assistant coach
of local recreation teams and a dancer.
</P>
<P>
   She was brought to the hospital after exhibiting symptoms more
than two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   ''Lauren was a social, caring child who was totally active,''
her parents, Lynn and Donna Mansel, wrote in a statement to The Day
of New London.
</P>
<P>
   ''Sixteen days ago she was excited about starting seventh grade
and now she's gone. It's been devastating to our entire family,''
the Mansels wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Family members say they don't know how Lauren ingested the
bacteria.
</P>
<P>
   Health officials say they believe Lauren's case is an isolated
one. They say there is no public health threat.
</P>
<P>
   An epidemiologist from the Department of Public Health will
investigate Mansel's death.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's no information at this point that people would need to
be concerned about an E. coli outbreak,'' said Arthur Cohen,
director of the Uncas Health District, which covers Montville and
Norwich.
</P>
<P>
   ''In many cases you can't determine the source,'' Cohen said.
''It's a detective job.''
</P>
<P>
   One form of E. coli, 0157:H7, can be fatal, according to
officials at the state Department of Public Health.
</P>
<P>
   People can contract the bacteria by eating contaminated, rare or
inadequately cooked meat. E. Coli can be spread via unwashed hands.
</P>
<P>
   The Mansels have established a fund to help teach Connecticut
residents about E. coli.
</P>
<P>
   ''The public is just not made aware enough of the dangers of E.
coli and prevention,'' Lynn and Donna Mansel wrote. ''No family
should have to go through what we are going through.''
</P>
<P>
   Donations may be sent to the Lauren A. Mansel E. coli Awareness
and Education Fund, c/o the Connecticut Children's Medical Center
Foundation, 12 Charter Oak Place, Hartford, CT 06106.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
