<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-17 13:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Palestinians Held for Common Crimes  </HEADLINE>
By JACK KATZENELL
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM (AP) -- Police accusations that militant Israeli
Muslims had planned widespread anti-Israel violence are misplaced,
a prosecutor said Sunday, casting official doubt on a claim that
sparked Arab outrage last week.
</P>
<P>
   Haifa District Attorney Lili Borishansky told The Associated
Press that the police files she received concerning the arrests 41
Arabs from the town of Umm al-Fahm and three West Bank Palestinians
contain no evidence of planned terror.
</P>
<P>
   Last Tuesday, announcing the arrests on suspicion of arson,
unlawful association, incitement to violence, trafficking in arms
and related offenses Northern Israel police commander Alik Ron
suggested that they were part of a pattern of planned terror.
</P>
<P>
   That was not the case, according to the files, Borishansky said.
''All I can say is that the files submitted to us contain no
evidence of nationalist motivation for the offenses.''
</P>
<P>
   The torchings of houses and businesses were acts of revenge for
a double murder committed in 1999 over a property dispute, she
said, and had nothing to do with the Islamic Movement, a political
party that controls Umm el-Fahm and other Arab local authorities.
</P>
<P>
   The arms trafficking was motivated purely by greed, not
anti-Israel intentions, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Ron painted the arrests as indicative of a pattern of violence
emerging among Israeli Arabs -- a group that largely avoided joining
the Palestinians during the 1987-93 Palestinian uprising.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is a long time since such serious nationalist activity with
such serious intentions has been uncovered,'' among Israel's Arab
minority Ron told a news conference.
</P>
<P>
   He accused the Islamic Movement, which has representatives in
parliament, of fomenting nationalist activity through inflammatory
sermons preached in the mosques.
</P>
<P>
   Ron's statements sparked an angry reaction from Israeli Arabs,
who say they are typical of an Israeli establishment that still
treats them as second-class citizens, and that has neglected their
towns and villages.
</P>
<P>
   About 30,000 Arabs attended a rally of the Islamic Movement in
Umm el-Fahm Friday. Many of those present were not Islamic
fundamentalists or not religious at all.
</P>
<P>
   Newspaper editorials accused Ron of having united the entire
Arab community in an anti-government protest.
</P>
<P>
   Arab legislators called Ron a racist and demanded his dismissal,
saying they had evidence Ron was already plotting a post-police
career in the hard-line Likud party, a charge Likud activists hotly
denied
</P>
<P>
   Police Minister Shlomo Ben-Ami hinted that he had reservations
about Ron's statements. Asked if Ron had shown the sufficient
sensitivity, Ben-Ami said ''I certainly have something to say to
him,'' but would not elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   Borishanky, who has already submitted indictments against some
of the suspects, denied reports of tension between Ron and the
prosecution over his statements about the case.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-17-00 1352 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
