<HEADLINE> Dolly Parton Does Country on Film  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   COOKEVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- Dolly Parton has appeared in films
before.
</P>
<P>
   But the entertainer admits that the prospect of appearing on an
IMAX movie screen seven stories tall has her feeling a little
intimidated.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm already larger than life, but in this movie I'm gonna be
bigger than a cow,'' a smiling Parton said last week while filming
sessions for a new IMAX film about country music.
</P>
<P>
   ''Lord, I'm scared to see it, but I'm proud to be part of it.''
</P>
<P>
   The as-yet untitled large-format movie is a project of Gaylord
Entertainment Co., which owns the Grand Ole Opry among other major
country music entertainment properties. It is scheduled to premiere
in Nashville in June and eventually go on the IMAX theater circuit.
</P>
<P>
   The movie showcases country music and various subgenres
including bluegrass, mountain, gospel, honky-tonk, rockabilly,
Western swing, cowboy and contemporary country.
</P>
<P>
   The cast includes The Dixie Chicks, Martina McBride, Alan
Jackson, Vince Gill, Loretta Lynn, Lyle Lovett, LeAnn Rimes, Tim
McGraw, Dwight Yoakam, Marty Stuart, Earl Scruggs, Alison Krauss
and many others.
</P>
</TEXT>
