<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-17 14:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Analysis of new Conservative Party ad  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   An analysis of a new television advertisement from
the
Conservative Party.
<TEXT>
<P>
   TIME: 30 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   TITLE: See Your Doctor.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCER: Warfield &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   SUMMARY AND TEXT: The ad, on behalf of Rep. Rick Lazio, takes
Lazio opponent Hillary Rodham Clinton to task for her role as the
head of a presidential commission charged with reshaping the
nation's health care system in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   The ad opens with an unflattering picture of the first lady and
a male voice asking, ''Remember the last time we trusted Hillary
Clinton with an important job in Washington?''
</P>
<P>
   A female hand, meant to be Clinton's, is shown playing the
children's game ''Operation.'' She is performing poorly, setting
off the game's buzzer and sending sparks flying. The narrator says
that Clinton ''proposed a government-run system, a bureaucratic
plan of rationing that destroyed your choice of doctors.''
</P>
<P>
   The narrator adds, that Clinton ''worked in secret and had to be
sued to disclose the details.''
</P>
<P>
   The ad concludes with the narrator saying, ''So if you trust
Hillary Clinton, maybe you should see your doctor, while you still
can.''
</P>
<P>
   ANALYSIS: The ad goes after what could be one of Clinton's
vulnerable spots: Her handling of the Clinton administration's
failed universal health care plan. Clinton led closed-door meetings
with policy experts, keeping the public in the dark about what was
going on. Once the plan became public, it died a quick death, in
part because of concerns about its high costs, the federal
government's broad role in managing care, and the fact that people
may not have been able to choose their own physicians.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has acknowledged that she did not handle the health care
plan well, and the Lazio campaign has hammered her on the issue of
late, questioning her management style and judgment, and seeking to
portray her as someone ill-equipped to take on complicated issues
that require sensitive handling.
</P>
<P>
   The word ''trust'' is emphasized in the ad, a continuation of an
effort by the Republican Party to label Clinton as untrustworthy,
or as Lazio says, ''Clintonesque.''
</P>
<P>
   The ad however, could cause unintended negative consequences for
Lazio. During last week's debate, Lazio theatrically challenged
Clinton to sign a contract barring the use of soft money in the
final two months of the campaign. The ad, however, is paid for by
the Conservative Party - a use of soft money that Lazio professes
to be opposed to.
</P>
<P>
   -----------------
</P>
<P>
   Analysis by Timothy Williams, Associated Press Writer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-09-17-00 1446 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000917.0081 </DOCNO>
