<HEADLINE> Germans To Get Fuel Tax Relief  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN (AP) -- Traffic flowed relatively smoothly across Europe
on Sunday as truckers, farmers and others angry about climbing fuel
costs took a break after more than a week of protests.
</P>
<P>
   The German goverment was preparing measures to help commuters
pay for gas and needy apartment dwellers pay for heating oil, the
Finance Ministry said Sunday. Details of the measures will be
announced in the next few days, a spokesman said on condition of
anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   The Welt am Sonntag newspaper reported that Chancellor Gerhard
Schroeder and Finance Minister Hans Eichel have already agreed to
earmark $444 million to help the 2 million Germans receiving
housing assistance to pay for heating oil this winter.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the government will raise the amount people who
drive to work can claim as a tax write-off from 30 to 40 cents per
kilometer, starting in 2001, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
   Truckers in Stockholm and Goteborg, Sweden's two biggest cities,
were planning protests Monday, according to spokesman Adam
Flamholc, with other cities joining Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   French truckers began demonstrations Sept. 4, winning a tax
break from Paris and inspiring protests in other countries.
Motorists in several other countries also have won concessions,
while governments in Britain and Germany have refused to cut fuel
taxes.
</P>
<P>
   German truckers were planning a nationwide day of protest on
Sept. 26.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-17-00 1453 </TRAILER>
