<HEADLINE> Officials look for statewide solutions to traffic congestion  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   With traffic congestion becoming a growing concern in
Connecticut for commuters and businesses, officials are vowing to
take statewide action to ease the gridlock.
<TEXT>
<P>
   State and business leaders have scheduled a transportation
summit for Sept. 28 at the Sheraton Hotel in East Hartford.
Findings from the summit will be submitted to the General Assembly
for possible action during its next session, which starts in
January.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're all tired of studies. We want to see action,'' said
House Speaker Moira Lyons, D-Stamford.
</P>
<P>
   Traffic must be addressed on a statewide basis to prevent the
problem from affecting the state's economic development, Lyons, an
organizer of the summit, said last week at a forum of the
Connecticut Regional Institute for the 21st Century.
</P>
<P>
   Statistics provided by Lyons' office indicate that economic
development in Connecticut is growing one-tenth slower than the
national average. The slower growth is attributed to a lack of
workers and transportation issues.
</P>
<P>
   A Connecticut Business &AMP; Industry Association survey of small-
and medium-sized companies released this month showed that 64
percent of respondents believed a first-rate transportation system
is important for economic growth.
</P>
<P>
   Rush hour traffic jams have already affected businesses in the
Stamford area, said Jack Condlin, president of the Stamford Chamber
of Commerce. Improvements to Interstate 95 are not keeping pace
with the city's burgeoning economy and the surge of workers coming
into the city, Condlin said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have the same basic highway system we had in the 1950s,''
Condlin said. ''It's an existing highway system that was strained
20 years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 60,000 people commute into Stamford daily, nearly double
the 35,000 who commuted into the city during the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Commuting to work also has become increasingly difficult for
drivers who depend on interstates 91 and 84, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   While the problem is apparent, solutions are more complicated.
There are limits to highway construction, said Tanya Court,
executive director of the Southwest Regional Planning Agency.
</P>
<P>
   ''Connecticut can no longer build its way out of congestion,''
Court said.
</P>
<P>
   Court advocated reducing rush hour traffic by having businesses
offer staggered work hours. She also said officials must find ways
to have more goods shipped on rail lines to reduce the number of
large trucks on the state's highways.
</P>
<P>
   A widening of I-91 is unlikely for many years, so more public
transit is needed, said Richard J. Porth, executive director of the
Capitol Region Council of Governments.
</P>
<P>
   Lyons said she wants the summit to be independent from political
considerations. She predicted that information from the event could
change the way state agencies approach transportation and economic
development projects.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-09-17-00 1604 </TRAILER>
