<HEADLINE> Gunfire unnerves Utica neighborhoods  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   UTICA, N.Y. (AP) - Residents here already plagued by crime have
been even more unnerved in the past week.
</P>
<P>
   At least eight people were wounded and three remain hospitalized
in five separate, unrelated shootings which ended Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Tim Julian said the city is trying to make a dent in the
violence. Last week, city and Oneida County officials formed a
Major Crimes Investigations Unit to combat serious felonies. The
task force will combine Utica officers with state troopers and
sheriffs deputies.
</P>
<P>
   ''I feel a little jumpy,'' said 60-year-old Annie Bell, who can
watch from her front porch as youths sell drugs on a nearby corner
that has become as popular as a fast-food drive-through. ''That's
the way most people feel.''
</P>
<P>
   Bell moved into her home in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was a nice street back then,'' she said. ''People around
here don't even come out here anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Even some pizza shops wont deliver to homes on her street, she
said, glancing at an empty, gravel-strewn corner farther down the
street.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's been getting really bad the past six or seven months,''
Bell said. ''Summer was really bad over here.''
</P>
<P>
   Philip Nardell, a 75-year-old Utican sometimes known as ''the
James Street Historian'' spoke sadly of the changes for the worse
he's seen over the years.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was down there that the boy was shot,'' he said, referring
to the Sept. 9 shooting of 16-year-old Eugene James.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's the kids,'' he said. ''They have no respect for people,
hanging out in the middle of the street making noise, using bad
language, very bad. When they get together in groups, anything
goes. That's why you don't see a lot of old people out. They just
treat people with contempt.''
</P>
<P>
   Nardell does not fault police. They do the best they can, he
said. But the prostitutes who turn away for a moment as a squad car
passes, or the drug dealers, scarcely pay attention.
</P>
<P>
   Sam Makarri knows all about the problems. Makarri closed his
discount store temporarily this summer to return to his native
Syria. While he was gone, youths broke into the store five
different times, smashing through the front window, the front door,
and the back door.
</P>
<P>
   The thieves sold his stock openly on the street, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I heard they were saying 'buy one, get three free,''' said
Makarri, who wasn't sure if he would re-open.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
