<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-17 16:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Onondaga Lake gets cleaner as ammonia levels fall  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   SYRACUSE, N.Y. (AP) - Scientists have detected the first signs
that Onondaga Lake, one of the most polluted bodies of water in the
country, is slowly but surely becoming cleaner.
</P>
<P>
   But the newfound evidence of a cleaner lake is the scourge of
healthy waterways across North America: the zebra mussel.
</P>
<P>
   For years, Onondaga Lake's waters were too toxic for zebra
mussels to proliferate. In 1997 and 1998, the lake had few, if any,
established zebra mussel colonies.
</P>
<P>
   That changed this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists at the Upstate Freshwater Institute in Syracuse last
month completed a study along the shoreline and found millions of
zebra mussels.
</P>
<P>
   The scientists estimate 200 to 600 million zebra mussels now
live in Onondaga Lake, a federal toxic waste site lined with
mercury and reputed to be the most polluted lake in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a zebra mussel infestation, absolutely,'' said Steven
Effler, Upstate's director of research. ''And it has the potential
for major water quality implications.''
</P>
<P>
   Onondaga County began a 15-year, $380 million cleanup effort
last year to stop sewage pollution of the lake, complying with a
federal court order.
</P>
<P>
   Effler said scientists saw the start of the zebra mussel boom as
levels of ammonia discharged from the county's sewage plant last
summer reached the lowest level recorded. The ammonia remained
extremely low this summer.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is the smoking gun on ammonia in Onondaga Lake,'' said
Effler, who has spent 25 years studying the lake's pollution. ''As
soon as the ammonia drops, we get the ammonia-sensitive organisms
returning to the lake. But who would have thought it would be zebra
mussels?''
</P>
<P>
   About 20 percent of the near-shore zone in Onondaga Lake is
covered with zebra mussels. In some spots, the mussels are
concentrated in densities of more than 3,000 per square meter.
</P>
<P>
   The dime-sized mollusks were discovered in North America in 1988
after entering the Great Lakes in ballast water of ships from
Europe. Since then, the mussels have spread to every large lake and
river across Central New York and down the Mississippi River as far
south as New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, zebra mussels attached themselves to almost any
hard surface in lakes and rivers, clogging water pipelines and
upsetting the ecological balance in those waterways. The zebra
mussel is the only freshwater mollusk that can firmly attach itself
to solid objects. Experts have predicted the mussels will cause $5
billion in damage in the United States.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-09-17-00 1611 </TRAILER>
