<HEADLINE> Clinton Celebrates Constitution  </HEADLINE>
By DEB RIECHMANN
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- President Clinton marked the 213th
anniversary of the signing of the Constitution by attending the
groundbreaking Sunday for a museum that will tell the historical
document's story.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also watched as 72 immigrants from 23 countries became
U.S. citizens. Earlier on the short visit, he spoke at a reception
that raised $50,000 for first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton's New
York Senate campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The main event was held at the future site of the National
Constitution Center, which will feature interactive displays, live
theater and high-tech exhibits about the Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   The $105 million museum is the cornerstone of a $200 million
renovation at Independence Mall, an area where Thomas Jefferson and
Benjamin Franklin strolled when the city was the seat of power in
America in the late 1770s.
</P>
<P>
   ''We revere the Constitution because it is at the core of who we
are,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   The protections guaranteed by the Constitution were cited by
Sen. Arlen Specter, R-Pa., who joined the president on stage and
mentioned the government's handling of the Wen Ho Lee case. Lee is
the nuclear scientist who went free last week after pleading guilty
to taking classified material from Los Alamos National Laboratory.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's hard to understand how a man can be a major threat to
national security one day and walk free the next,'' Specter said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, too, has raised questions about the fact that Lee's
plea came shortly after the government argued that he needed to
remain in jail without bail. The president said that flew in the
face of the nation's opposition to ''abusive executive authority.''
</P>
<P>
   During the naturalization ceremony, Clinton joined in reciting
the Pledge of Allegiance.
</P>
<P>
   As the president and Susan Yuh, a 24-year-old from South Korea,
signed their names to a construction beam suspended by a crane at
the museum site, a choir sang ''America'' and red, white, and blue
streamers fell over the audience of more than 500 people.
</P>
<P>
   ''About four months from now, I will change jobs and I will be
restored to the title that Harry Truman once said is the most
important title an American can have -- that of citizen,'' Clinton
said.
</P>
<P>
   ''This country is great because there are good people who get up
everyday and do their very best and live their dreams ... because
this country has a system inscribed in the Constitution that gives
them the maximum opportunity to do just that.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's first stop in Philadelphia was the City Tavern, a
reconstruction of a late 18th century landmark where members of the
First Continental Congress gathered in the 1770s. The event raised
about $50,000 for the Senate campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also turned to presidential politics, noting that after
the parties' nominating conventions, the race becomes ''an
elaborate chess game'' for the 270 electoral votes needed to win
the White House.
</P>
<P>
   ''Pennsylvania has 23 votes and it's also in the heartland of
America with Ohio and Michigan and Illinois and Wisconsin and
Minnesota,'' Clinton said. ''And if you have Pennsylvania, it
drastically increases your changes of carrying New Jersey and of
carrying Ohio. No Republican has been elected since the Civil War
without carrying Ohio and it is very hard for a Democrat to be
elected without carrying Pennsylvania.''
</P>
<P>
   The latest polls give Vice President Al Gore, the Democratic
nominee, wide leads over Republican George W. Bush in Pennsylvanian
and Illinois, an edge in Michigan, and a tie in Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic internal surveys reflect the same general picture in
those states, except they are not quite as far ahead in
Pennsylvania. Republican internal polling suggests that Bush is in
better shape -- ahead in Ohio, close or slightly ahead in Michigan
and trailing slightly in Illinois and Pennsylvania.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-17-00 1655 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
