<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-17 17:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indian PM To Be Honored at Dinner  </HEADLINE>
By LARRY MARGASAK
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The White House prepared a lavish official
dinner Sunday for Indian Prime Minister Atal Bihari Vajpayee, more
evidence of a warming relationship with a nuclear power in a
dangerous part of the world.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to the cold shoulder given last week to the military
ruler of India's nuclear rival, Pakistan, President Clinton invited
Vajpayee to a South Lawn Pavilion tent filled with fall fruits and
tables adorned with gold-base plates, cream china and gold candles.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 700 guests were invited for the largest official dinner
of the Clinton presidency to honor a single visiting dignitary.
Only a NATO summit dinner for 19 heads of state was larger.
</P>
<P>
   With crystal chandeliers hanging above tables bedecked with
hydrangea, guests were to feast on wild Copper River salmon with
red kuri squash and rice bean ragout for a main course. The dessert
menu included mango and banner lotus, litchis and raspberry sauce,
honey almond squares and chocolate coconut bars.
</P>
<P>
   For entertainment, the president and Hillary Rodham Clinton
invited the Chamber Music Society of Lincoln Center in New York,
where the first lady is seeking a Senate seat.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning with Vajpayee's address Thursday to Congress, the
prime minister's visit took on a serious tone because of India's
resumption of nuclear testing in 1998, its explosive feud with
Pakistan and its rocky relationship with the United States during
the Cold War.
</P>
<P>
   In this presidential election year, both parties are courting
Indian-Americans, who are becoming an important political force
that is influential in U.S. high-tech industries.
</P>
<P>
   The guest list was dominated by Indian-Americans from all walks
of life. Among those invited: Clarence Chandran, chief operating
officer of Nortel Networks; NASA astronaut Dr. Kalpana Chawla; Dr.
B. K. Angnihotri, chancellor of the Southern University Law Center;
Dr. Satya Ahuja, past president of the American Association of
Physicians of Indian Origin; tennis player Vijay Amritaj.
</P>
<P>
   Celebrities included model-turned environmental activist
Christie Brinkley, actor Chevy Chase, singer Melissa Etheridge and
author Elie Wiesel.
</P>
<P>
   The dinner was a big contrast from the recent reception for
Pakistani ruler Gen. Pervez Musharraf, who was in New York for the
Millennium Summit. Clinton kept his distance from the military
ruler who overthrew an elected government and leads a country with
links to radical Islam.
</P>
<P>
   Vajpayee, 75, has not had an easy time physically on this visit.
He has chronic pain in his left knee from osteoarthritis, which
erodes the cartilage around the knee. He will have knee replacement
surgery in India.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: State Department background on India:
http://www.state.gov/www/regions/sa/index.html
</P>
<P>
   Embassy of India: http://www.indianembassy.org
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister's Office of India: http://pmindia.nic.in
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-17-00 1701 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
