<DOCNO> APW20000917.0097 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-17 17:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Warns Iraq About Aggression  </HEADLINE>
By DEAN VISSER
<TEXT>
<P>
   SINGAPORE (AP) -- U.S. Defense Secretary William Cohen warned
Iraqi leader Saddam Hussein on Sunday to avoid taking any
''aggressive action'' against his country's neighbors, saying the
United States and Britain could defeat any threat.
</P>
<P>
   Kuwait urged world leaders Sunday to take steps to restrain Iraq
from threatening the emirate or stability in the Persian Gulf as a
whole after Baghdad warned last week that it would take action to
stop what it called Kuwaiti theft of its oil.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen said Saddam should ''understand that the United States and
our British friends are fully prepared to take whatever action is
necessary to prevent him from trying to repeat his past actions.''
</P>
<P>
   ''We can certainly handle Saddam should he choose to take any
kind of aggressive action,'' he said aboard the USS Germantown, a
warship docked in Singapore, one of the stops on his six-nation
Asian tour.
</P>
<P>
   Tension increased in the Middle East last week when Iraq accused
Kuwait of drilling wells that allow it to siphon Iraqi oil and
warned that it would move to halt its smaller neighbor's action.
</P>
<P>
   Iraq historically has accused Kuwait of stealing its oil, one of
the justifications it made for invading in 1990. A U.S.-led
coalition army drove Iraq from Kuwait seven months later.
</P>
<P>
   In the past two weeks, Iraq also has flown a jet fighter over
Saudi airspace for the first time in more than a decade.
</P>
<P>
   Kuwaiti Cabinet ministers discussed Iraq's recent threats
Sunday, Interior Minister Sheik Mohammed Al Khaled Al Sabah said,
calling the Iraqi accusation ''baseless'' and an attempt to create
regional instability.
</P>
<P>
   Kuwait ''calls on the international community to take serious
steps against the Iraqi regime's threats and to take all the needed
measures to guarantee that it does not repeat its threats against
Kuwait and regional countries,'' the state-run Kuwait News Agency
quoted Sheik Mohammed as saying.
</P>
<P>
   Defense Minister Sheik Salem Al Sabah said in an interview
published Sunday the Iraqi leadership ''will pay a high price this
time if it carries out any foolish military act against Kuwait.''
</P>
<P>
   ''The Iraqi regime's continuous threats do not scare us, whether
they are serious or for political consumption,'' Sheik Salem was
quoted as telling Al-Rai Al-Am daily.
</P>
<P>
   An Iraqi official said late Sunday that Baghdad was not making
threats and that it meant only that it would take ''technical
measures'' to prevent Kuwaiti theft of its oil. The Iraqi comments
were ''explained by others differently as it suited them,'' the
official said on condition he not be named.
</P>
<P>
   Friction between the United States and Iraq has been rising,
mainly over renewed efforts to have U.N. inspectors search for
hidden weapons of mass destruction in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has announced plans to give $8 million to
Saddam's political foes and Secretary of State Madeleine Albright
warned Iraq risks American attack if it crosses U.S. ''red lines.''
</P>
<P>
   Albright also met with Iraqi dissidents to discuss building a
war crimes case against Saddam and took several opportunities
during the recent U.N. Millennium summit to denounce Saddam and his
government.
</P>
<P>
   Most recently, Saddam ordered his party members last week to
conduct military training year-round; he said it was necessary
''because our enemy is fighting us in all fields.'' Military
training is usually conducted during crises and summer vacations
only.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-17-00 1715 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000917.0098 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-17 17:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Interest rises in race for Boehlert's seat  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   UTICA, N.Y. (AP) - A lackluster primary showing and tensions
over an Indian land claim have combined to heighten anticipation
over veteran Congressman Sherwood Boehlert's re-election bid.
</P>
<P>
   Boehlert, 63, is seeking his 10th term in the House of
Representatives. In last week's primary, he narrowly defeated David
Vickers, a 35-year-old Spanish teacher at Hamilton High School.
Vickers, who will run in the general election on the Conservative
and Right To Life lines, has been telling voters they need a change
in the 23rd Congressional District.
</P>
<P>
   Dairy farmer and political rookie Richard Engelbrecht is the
choice of the Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   The candidates have agreed to at least three debates and those
meetings and money may determine the outcome.
</P>
<P>
   Boehlert spent $150 for every $1 Vickers spent in the months
before the primary, which Boehlert won 56 percent to 44 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Utica pollster John Zogby has predicted that Boehlert, with the
Republican and Independence parties' lines, will win decisively
over Vickers.
</P>
<P>
   ''To be sure, (Boehlert's) Republican base will come out to
vote,'' Zogby said. ''He'll win and win big, but he can expect Mr.
Vickers ... to be looking over his shoulder for a while.''
</P>
<P>
   Boehlert blamed low voter turnout for his unconvincing
performance at the polls while Vickers complained the media hasn't
taken his candidacy seriously.
</P>
<P>
   Boehlert's supporters didn't come out on the rainy Primary Day,
possibly because he didn't do ''the aggressive kind of
get-out-to-vote campaign,'' Zogby said.
</P>
<P>
   Vickers rallied a ''more passionate following'' for his right
wing, pro-life, anti-Oneida Indian land claim agenda, Zogby said.
</P>
<P>
   Zogby predicts Vickers won't add to the 10,000-plus votes he
mustered in the primary. But Vickers has other ideas. He said he
will focus on convincing voters he could get results in the
nation's capital.
</P>
<P>
   ''I will address issues. I will not sit on fences,'' Vickers
said. ''I'm going to offer a very positive alternative.''
</P>
<P>
   Engelbrecht, with the spotlight on his opponents during primary
season, has lurked in the background. Zogby said the 56-year-old
Madison farmer will get votes on the Democratic line and from Green
Party members but doesn't pose much of a threat to Boehlert.
</P>
<P>
   But Engelbrecht, a 28-year member of the Madison-Oneida BOCES
Board of Education, said Boehlert and Vickers will split much of
the Republican vote, leaving the door open for him.
</P>
<P>
   To have a chance, Engelbrecht knows he has to get his name and
message out in Oneida County. He said he has visited other counties
in the 23rd district but has yet to make his presence felt in
Oneida County.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Boehlert said he will step up his publicity
campaign, especially in Madison County and western Oneida County,
where the Oneida Indian Nation land claim is paramount to many
voters.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have not been able to prove to people in the land claim we
have been working on their behalf,'' Boehlert said. ''I have to
redouble my efforts to prove to the landowners that I'm working in
their interest and I have been for some time now.''
</P>
<P>
   Boehlert said he will continue to tout his 18-year record of
fighting for district residents in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ''The point is, in a campaign you have to tell people what you
have done,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But voters in the land-claim territory who say Boehlert hasn't
done enough to calm their fears of losing their land helped Vickers
get 66 percent of the primary in Madison County, his home turf.
</P>
<P>
   The Oneidas are seeking compensation for 250,000 acres in Oneida
and Madison counties they claim were wrongly taken from them in the
late 18th and early 19th centuries.
</P>
<P>
   Tensions have been high in the land-claim territory since
December 1998, when the Oneidas asked the court to include the
owners of some 20,000 parcels as defendants in the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Engelbrecht said he can steal some votes from residents in the
land-claim territory as well. He favors a quick resolution to all
Indian land claims and said the state and federal governments
should pay Indians for past wrongs.
</P>
<P>
   He also wants to abolish the federal Bureau of Indian Affairs,
which he said has ''moved and manipulated the Native American
people to a point of near destruction.''
</P>
<P>
   Vickers, meanwhile, said he will continue to raise questions
about Boehlert's Congressional record.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's blood in the water, and I think everyone knows that,''
he said. ''He's got to fend off a lot of sharks.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
