<BODY>
<HEADLINE> As suburbs develop, cartographer tries to record web of new roads  </HEADLINE>
phqjp
<TEXT>
<P>
   KING OF PRUSSIA, Pa. (AP) - Few know better than Andy Amsterdam
about how Philadelphia's suburbs have turned into a confounding web
of Picket Post Ways, Red Fox Circles, and Hunting Horn Lanes.
</P>
<P>
   Amsterdam is a mapmaker and part of his job is making sure the
maps he produces keep up with new streets, new names and new
developments.
</P>
<P>
   And there are more than ever.
</P>
<P>
   In 1983, there were about 18,000 streets in the four
Pennsylvania counties bordering Philadelphia. Today, there are
nearly 40,000.
</P>
<P>
   Amsterdam, a mapmaker of 40 years, owns Franklin Maps in King of
Prussia. His father, Lewis, started the company in 1928 and it
remains one of only a handful of local mapmakers, with annual sales
of about 150,000 maps. Its books cover 19 counties in southeast and
central Pennsylvania and south and central New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Mapping Philadelphia is easy - its 2,792 streets remain
essentially unchanged year-to-year.
</P>
<P>
   The suburbs, however, are a cartographer's nightmare.
</P>
<P>
   As chief researcher, Amsterdam digs through tax files, deed
books, zoning maps and building permits to keep up with
development. He also drives through every new development in search
of street signs, sometimes before the pavement is even put down.
</P>
<P>
   Franklin's county maps are generally updated every 18 months and
it takes the company about three months to produce a map. Still, by
the time a map is printed, it is probably out of date.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're getting to the point where we'll no longer be able to
show all the streets on the map - there's so many,'' said Mike
Stokes, a Montgomery County planner.
</P>
<P>
   There are also practical hurdles.
</P>
<P>
   Newer developments employ spidery cul-de-sacs that, when shown
on a map, are too short for the grandiose names they'd been given.
</P>
<P>
   ''Yuppie names like Fox Hunt Drive and Blue Jay Way,'' Stokes
said.
</P>
<P>
   Traditionally, mapmakers draw an arrow from short streets to a
list of names printed on a blank spot. But there aren't many blank
spots anymore.
</P>
<P>
   ''The areas where we used to list names are developed,'' Stokes
said.
</P>
<P>
   As Franklin continues to add maps, it moves into counties with
wide expanses of open space being gobbled up by development.
</P>
<P>
   In just two days this summer, Amsterdam tried to visit about
half of Cumberland County's 34 municipalities.
</P>
<P>
