<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-17 17:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Senate race seems stagnant; outcome hangs on huge undecided block  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEWARK, N.J. (AP) - With plenty of summertime distractions, New
Jersey voters have shown little interest in the Senate race and
there's been little movement in the candidates' standing, according
to the latest Star-Ledger/Eagleton-Rutgers poll.
</P>
<P>
   Democrat John Corzine was clinging to a small lead over
Republican Bob Franks among likely voters, but had a respectable
advantage over Franks among registered voters.
</P>
<P>
   A lot could change by Election Day, with 21 percent of New
Jersey adults saying they were undecided, and 47 percent of voters
saying they could change their mind by the time they enter the
voting booth.
</P>
<P>
   ''As far as New Jersey voters are concerned, it is as if their
Senate race has gone into hibernation,'' Cliff Zukin, a Rutgers
University professor of public policy and the poll's director, told
The Star-Ledger for Sunday's editions.
</P>
<P>
   ''We see little evidence of increased attention to the race,
familiarity with the candidates or comfort in having made a
decision,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A total of 670 New Jersey residents were interviewed by
telephone between Sept. 6 and 13 for the poll.
</P>
<P>
   Among poll respondents saying they are likely to vote, 45
percent favored Corzine, a former Wall Street executive, compared
with 36 percent backing Franks, a four-term congressman
representing New Jersey's 7th District. But with the poll's margin
of error, 4 percentage points for most responses, Corzine could be
leading by as little as 1 percentage point.
</P>
<P>
   Among registered voters, Corzine has a more comfortable lead, 47
percent to 32 percent, which is slightly bigger than the
millionaire's 10-point lead among registered voters in a
Star-Ledger/Eagleton-Rutgers poll taken right after the two men won
their respective primaries on June 6.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the slight improvement for Corzine, the percentage of
undecided voters has stayed about the same.
</P>
<P>
   In part, that's because Franks, who has had trouble raising
campaign funds, so far has aired no television commercials, while
Corzine, who spent a record $35 million on his primary campaign,
halted TV ads until Labor Day.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the Corzine-Franks race has been overshadowed by
heavy coverage of New York's Senate race, between first lady
Hillary Rodham Clinton and U.S. Rep. Rick Lazio. For instance, the
poll found only 14 percent of respondents had heard or read roughly
the same amount about the Franks-Corzine race as about the
Clinton-Lazio contest.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is where the lack of in-state commercial television hurts
New Jersey,'' Zukin told the newspaper. ''It is much harder to
become an informed voter in New Jersey then in most states.''
</P>
<P>
   Public interest in New Jersey's Senate race was barely half as
high as interest in the presidential race pitting Vice President Al
Gore against Texas Gov. George W. Bush; 34 percent told pollsters
they had ''a lot'' of interest in the Senate race, compared to 61
percent with ''a lot'' of interest in the presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Even the ''decided'' voters were wishing for more information
about the two candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Marilyn Gorski, 75, of Piscataway planned to vote for Corzine
but complained he has not given enough specifics about his plans to
reform education, health care and Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   ''He saying a lot, but he's not saying how he's going to do
these things,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   David Rebovich, a Rider University political scientist, said the
many voters who are undecided or open to change give Franks a
chance to overcome Corzine's money advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ''It means Franks is still in the ballpark,'' he said. ''He can
look to the one-on-one debates next month to help him sway some
undecided voters who still are looking for cues.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
