<HEADLINE> The Nation's Weather  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   Tropical Storm Gordon battered Florida's west coast
Sunday,
dumping heavy rain, threatening a storm surge and spawning at least
one torainado.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The storm was at hurricane strength for much of the day, and was
due to make landfall Sunday evening. By midafterainoon, five inches
of rain had fallen in parts of Florida, scattered flooding was
reported in St. Petersburg, and a torainado was reported in Palm
Beach County.
</P>
<P>
   Hurricane warainings were in effect from Ochlockonee River, north
to the Anna Maria Island area along the Gulf Coast of Florida.
Tropical storm warainings were posted for much of the remainder of
Florida's Gulf Coast, and high wind warainings were in effect in
interior areas.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the remainder of the United States was quiet. From the
mid-Atlantic states into the central and southerain Plains, skies
were clear to partly cloudy.
</P>
<P>
   Clouds and some showers spread over the northerain Rockies. The
remainder of the West was fair and dry.
</P>
<P>
   Temperatures in the Lower 48 states Sunday ranged from 98
degrees in Blythe, Calif., to 34 degrees in Truckee, Calif. With
the wind, the moraining temperature in Truckee felt like 23 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
