<HEADLINE> Candidates troll for ethnic votes but soft money fight rages  </HEADLINE>
By BETH J. HARPAZ
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - The Senate candidates spent Sunday trolling for
votes with old-fashioned campaigning in ethnic neighborhoods,
churches and street fairs.
</P>
<P>
   But behind the handshakes and voter greetings, the campaigns
continued to battle over unregulated donations known as ''soft
money.''
</P>
<P>
   Republican candidate Rep. Rick Lazio of Long Island said he had
just received a legal opinion from his advisers giving him
''clearance'' to ask outside groups ''to refrain from campaigning
or pursuing any advertising on our behalf or against my opponent.
And if they do, which I don't believe they will, I'm going to
disassociate myself from that.''
</P>
<P>
   Karen Dunn, a spokeswoman for Hillary Rodham Clinton's campaign,
called Lazio's statement ''empty rhetoric. If he really wanted to
eliminate soft money and independent expenditures from this race,
he would get written commitments from his allies to stop the
attacks against Hillary.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week during a televised debate, Lazio waved a contract in
Clinton's face that he said would ban soft money.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton refused to sign the pledge because it does not prohibit
the ads and letters from outside supporters but merely ''calls on''
them to voluntarily refrain.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, Lazio has said he has no control over activities by
others on his behalf - a claim he reiterated Sunday when asked
about a new ad by the Conservative Party that mocks the first
lady's failed effort to reform health care.
</P>
<P>
   The text of the ad appeared in Sunday's New York Times, but when
he was asked about the ad, Lazio said: ''I haven't seen it. I
haven't seen a text of it, so I don't really have much to comment
on about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton told reporters Sunday that the new soft-money ad is
''just a further example of him saying one thing and doing
something else. Certainly his allies have gone forward with their
campaign of insults, on the air, in the mails, in every other way
they can. I don't think he was ever serious about (a ban). It was
simply a debate stunt.''
</P>
<P>
   But Lazio has also noted that his campaign does not have its own
soft-money account, while Clinton has raised $3 million in soft
money for her candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   Both candidates were warmly received by voters Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was cheered and praised as she attended services at four
black churches in Queens, while Lazio was repeatedly greeted as the
''anti-Hillary'' in Jewish neighborhoods in Brooklyn and the Bronx
and at an Irish fair on Long Island.
</P>
<P>
   ''Who's everyone voting for?'' Lazio asked as he walked into the
back room of a kosher deli where a group from a Jewish center was
having lunch.
</P>
<P>
   ''Not Hillary!'' shouted Muriel Rubin in response.
</P>
<P>
   ''The decision is as easy as ABC - anybody but Clinton,'' added
Carol Hagler, a teacher.
</P>
<P>
   Moshe Tyberg shook Lazio's hand on a street in Flatbush and said
of Clinton: ''There's just something I don't like about her. So the
alternative, as long as he's a decent fellow, and he seems to be a
nice guy, then definitely he has my support.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Clinton was greeted with assurances of support from
black churchgoers.
</P>
<P>
   ''You are in friendly quarters,'' the Rev. James Kelly of New
Jerusalem Baptist Church told her. ''The love and admiration we
have for you is well-known and will be proven in the ballot box.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton thanked worshippers in each church ''for your prayers
over the last eight years. I know my husband, my daughter and I
have felt the strength of those prayers ... They have uplifted and
sustained us, and I am also convinced they have protected us.''
</P>
<P>
   She also acknowledged that despite the economic boom, some
Americans are ''still laboring in the shadows of life, still on the
margins, still left behind,'' and promised to work for better
schools, health care and continued economic progress.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also made a stop at the Race for the Cure in Central
Park, a fund-raiser for breast cancer research.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio's final stop was at an Irish fair in Port Washington,
where he was introduced to voters by Rep. Peter King, the Long
Island Republican who had hoped to run for Senate before Lazio
emerged as the GOP favorite.
</P>
<P>
   The most recent poll on the race, in Sunday's Daily News, showed
voters favoring Clinton over Lazio 48 to 43 percent. The survey's
margin of error is 4 points.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Sunday, James Carville, an unofficial Clinton campaign
adviser, launched a harsh attack against Lazio during an appearance
Sunday morning on NBC's ''Meet the Press,'' calling the congressman
''a little clown not even worth glove-slapping.''
</P>
<P>
   ''He's just a little guy just trying so hard to get noticed by
people, he just crosses the line,'' Carville said when asked about
Lazio's aggressive performance against Clinton in their first
debate Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Carville was taken immediately to task by fellow ''Meet the
Press'' guest, his wife Mary Matalin, a Republican political
consultant.
</P>
<P>
   ''In the short time we've been on, he's called a Senate
candidate - a candidate for the United States Senate who clearly
showed he was up to the job and of the stature of the first lady -
'stupid, Little Ricky, a little clown.' This is not the dialogue of
the race,'' Matalin said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-09-17-00 2035 </TRAILER>
