<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-17 21:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Central Sudan Riots Kill Two  </HEADLINE>
By MOHAMED OSMAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   KHARTOUM, Sudan (AP) -- Students and the unemployed rioted Sunday
in a central Sudanese city, burning government buildings and banks
during hours of clashes with security forces that left at least two
dead and several injured, the governor of White Nile state said.
</P>
<P>
   The riots started in the city of Kosti, 175 miles south of
Khartoum, when students demonstrated against mandatory military
service, Gov. Badawi el-Kheir Idriss told state run television.
Then, he said, scores of the unemployed joined them and began
burning government cars, the local government-run radio station,
the provincial office building, banks and police stations.
</P>
<P>
   Idriss said ''joint forces'' -- apparently police and army units
-- enforced calm on the area after two people, including a student,
were killed. He said several people were injured, but was not
specific.
</P>
<P>
   Idriss accused ''instigative sides'' of provoking the violence,
a veiled reference to followers of the Popular National Congress
Party, an opposition group headed by Islamic ideologue Hassan
Turabi.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's riots follow last week's unrest in the western city of
al-Fashir where a woman was killed and 16 people were injured,
reportedly over delays in the start of classes.
</P>
<P>
   Also last week, five people were injured when hundreds of
students rioted in the eastern city of Port Sudan against an
attempt to require them to pay damage deposits on textbooks.
</P>
<P>
   Turabi's PNC issued a statement Sunday saying that 53 of its
members had been arrested following last week's riots in al-Fashir
and Port Sudan.
</P>
<P>
   For years, Turabi was widely seen as the driving force behind
President Omar el-Bashir's government. But late last year,
el-Bashir accused Turabi of trying to undermine him. El-Bashir
dissolved Parliament -- stripping Turabi of his powerful position as
speaker -- and imposed a state of emergency.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile on Sunday, John Garang, leader of Sudan's biggest
rebel group, said he is ready to meet el-Bashir to try to end the
country's 17-year civil war, which has claimed 2 million lives in
fighting and war-related famine.
</P>
<P>
   Garang's comments follow last week's conference in neighboring
Eritrea of the National Democratic Alliance, an umbrella for
Sudanese opposition groups including Garang's Sudan People's
Liberation Army. An alliance statement said a ''political solution
is the best way to end the war.''
</P>
<P>
   El-Bashir said Saturday he was ready to meet with the rebels to
secure an end to the war. He hasn't met Garang since being
installed as president in a 1989 coup.
</P>
<P>
   The rebels are fighting for a more fair distribution of national
wealth as well as for an end to what they view as domination of a
varied country by a Muslim and Arabized clique in Khartoum.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-17-00 2157 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000917.0136 </DOCNO>
