<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-17 22:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Day 4 of the Sydney Olympic Games  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   
STARS:
Monday:
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tom Malchow, St. Paul, Minn., broke the Olympic record in the
200-meter butterfly by finishing his preliminary in 1 minute, 56.25
seconds. He broke the mark of 1:56.26, set by American Marvin
Stewart in winning gold at the 1992 Barcelona Games.
</P>
<P>
   Marty Nothstein, Trexlertown, Pa., covered 200 meters in sprint
cycling qualifying in 10.166, the fastest among 19 riders and
narrowly off the Olympic record of 10.129.
</P>
<P>
   Cai Yalin, China, won the men's 10-meter air rifle gold medal
with an Olympic-record score of 696.4 -- breaking the mark of silver
medalist Artem Khadjibekov.
Sunday:
</P>
<P>
   Lori Harrigan, Las Vegas, threw the first solo softball
no-hitter in a 6-0 victory over Canada.
</P>
<P>
   Simon Whitfield, Canada, won the men's triathlon in 1 hour, 48
minutes, 24 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Dolan, Arlington, Va., broke his own world record by
swimming the 400-meter individual medley in 4 minutes, 11.76
seconds. Dolan, who lowered his 4:12.30 set at the 1994 world
championships, won his second consecutive Olympic gold in the
event.
</P>
<P>
   Inge de Bruijn, the Netherlands, broke her own world mark by
winning the 100 fly in 56.61 seconds.
MEDALS:
</P>
<P>
   A total of 15 gold medals are awarded Monday after 14 were given
out Sunday in the second full day of competition.
WEATHER:
</P>
<P>
   The temperature was 75 degrees Monday morning (Sunday night EDT)
under partly cloudy skies.
SNARL:
</P>
<P>
   The Japanese softball team was delayed for almost an hour
because of a traffic jam caused by an accident. Japan's game
against China on Monday (Sunday night EDT) was delayed for 40
minutes and the following United States-Cuba was pushed back an
hour. ... The Monday afternoon boxing card was also delayed 30
minutes because of the late arrival of athletes.
SAMARANCH SERVICE:
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of Olympic officials, dignitaries and friends attended
a memorial service Monday (Sunday night EDT) for the wife of IOC
president Juan Antonio Samaranch, who died shortly after her
husband presided over the opening of the Sydney Games.
SURPRISING SILVER:
</P>
<P>
   Tara Nott, who tried two other sports before settling on
weightlifting only four years ago, won a surprise silver medal for
the United States as women's weightlifting made its Olympic debut
Sunday. Nott, never higher than ninth in the world championships,
placed second to Izabela Dragneva of Bulgaria at 106 pounds.
SWIMMING:
</P>
<P>
   Tom Dolan won the gold and Erik Vendt took the silver for the
United States in the 400-meter individual medley Sunday. ... Brooke
Bennett and Diana Munz extended the United States' distance
swimming legacy by winning gold and silver in the 400 freestyle.
... Jenny Thompson finished fifth in the 100 fly in her attempt to
win her first individual medal to go along with six team titles.
SOCCER STALEMATE:
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. women's soccer team hopes to improve on its 1-1 draw
with China on Sunday when it plays Nigeria on Wednesday. The
Americans need at least a draw to advance to the semifinals.
STIRRING FINISH:
</P>
<P>
   Down three goals with less than two minutes to play, the U.S.
women's water polo team rallied to tie Canada 8-8 and remain
undefeated in the first Olympic tournament. The final goal came
with just four seconds remaining.
SAME OLD STORY:
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. men's basketball team rolled to a 119-72 victory over
China, a team that it beat by 63 points in the 1996 Atlanta Games.
Ray Allen scored 21 points, Vince Carter had 16, Tim Hardaway and
Steve Smith added 12 each and Vin Baker 11 for the Americans, who
trailed 13-7. Allan Houston (jammed wrist) did not play for the
U.S. team, which will face Italy on Tuesday.
SPEAKING:
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm not concerned with records or time here. I want to save
something (for the final). It's about winning.'' -- Tom Malchow of
St. Paul, Minn., who broke the Olympic record in the 200-meter
butterfly by finishing his preliminary in 1 minute, 56.25 seconds
Monday (Sunday night EDT).
</P>
</TEXT>
