<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Colombia Gunmen Kidnap At Least 30  </HEADLINE>
By TIMOTHY PRATT
<TEXT>
<P>
   CALI, Colombia (AP) -- Gunmen kidnapped at least 30 people Sunday
from two restaurants located in the weekend playground of the
well-to-do outside Colombia's third-largest city in an operation
blamed on leftist rebels.
</P>
<P>
   About 50 armed men, many wearing military-style uniforms and
bulletproof vests, barged into the restaurants in the highlands
outside Cali on Sunday, police said. Gunmen also seized a couple
from a nearby farm.
</P>
<P>
   The mass kidnapping recalled the abduction on May 30, 1999, by
the National Liberation Army, or ELN, of 150 worshippers at a
Catholic Mass in Cali. All those hostages have since been released.
</P>
<P>
   Police told journalists at the scene of Sunday's kidnapping that
it may have been carried out by the ELN working with members of
Colombia's biggest rebel group, the Revolutionary Armed Forces of
Colombia, or FARC.
</P>
<P>
   ''We estimate that about 30 people were taken,'' said Cali
police commander Rafael Pardo. Other police officials put the
number of hostages between 25 and 40.
</P>
<P>
   The hostages were snatched from the Cabana Restaurant and the
Embajada de Ginebra restaurant, 10 miles outside Cali. Among those
taken was Alvaro Tenorio, owner of the Embajada de Ginebra, or
Embassy of Geneva.
</P>
<P>
   There were no immediate demands for ransom or claims of
responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   Eduardo de Lima and his wife Elena were kidnapped from a nearby
farm. De Lima's brother owns the De Lima Insurance Company, one of
the region's largest, police said.
</P>
<P>
   The hostage-takers struck Sunday where many residents of Cali go
to escape the tropical city's sweltering heat for a drive into the
nearby mountains and a Sunday meal. The two restaurants that were
targeted are among many that line the Via Al Mar, or Highway to the
Sea, which meanders toward the Pacific Ocean, 45 miles to the west.
</P>
<P>
   Colombia has one of the highest kidnapping rates in the world.
</P>
<P>
   For the first half of this year, 1,750 people were kidnapped,
according to Free Country Foundation, a private group. The FARC was
responsible for 477 and the ELN 381 of the kidnappings, Free
Country says.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-17-00 2252 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000917.0146 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-17 22:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Refugee Chief Heads To Afghanistan  </HEADLINE>
By MOHAMMED FAROOQ
<TEXT>
<P>
   HERAT, Afghanistan (AP) -- The U.N. refugee chief helped hundreds
of Afghan refugees return home Sunday, then made her own journey to
Herat for talks with the ruling Taliban on their poor human rights
record.
</P>
<P>
   The 836 refugees, crammed into 50 trucks piled high with
mattresses, wood, clothes and bicycles, left Quetta, in southwest
Pakistan, and traveled rutted roads to Kandahar, in southern
Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
   Sadako Ogata, the U.N. high commissioner for refugees, watched
as they received travel documents. Each returning refugee family
was given about $90, a sack of wheat and a plastic sheet for
shelter.
</P>
<P>
   Ogata said she was encouraged by their determination to rebuild
their lives in war-ravaged Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
   ''Most of the refugees do want to go back. I've seen that in
Pakistan,'' said Ogata, who is touring the region to draw attention
to the 2.6 million Afghan refugees in Pakistan and Iran.
</P>
<P>
   Refugees poured out of Afghanistan after the Soviet invasion in
1979, numbering more than 6 million in the 1980s. More than half
have returned, but there are still 2.6 million officially
registered in Pakistan and Iran.
</P>
<P>
   Ogata flew to the western Afghan city of Herat and met with the
Taliban, the hard-line Islamic group that has ruled most of
Afghanistan for the past four years.
</P>
<P>
   The Taliban received Ogata warmly and said they were ready for
more refugees to return, UNHCR spokesman Yusuf Hassan said.
</P>
<P>
   Before talks began, Ogata said, ''I will be telling the Taliban
to improve their education facilities and to stop the fighting so
that all these refugees could come back.''
</P>
<P>
   She also planned to raise human rights issues, including the
Taliban's treatment of women. Under the Taliban's extreme brand of
Islamic law, women are barred from most jobs, face great
difficulties in obtaining an education, and are not permitted to
leave their homes without a male relative.
</P>
<P>
   The Taliban control more than 90 percent of the country, but
with the economy in ruins, refugees have been slow to return.
</P>
<P>
   Mullah Masom, a refugee who returned Sunday, left Afghanistan in
1978 as political turmoil and unrest erupted.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have problems here with water shortages, and there are no
jobs,'' Masom said of life in the Pakistan camps. ''Now that there
is some peace, we have decided to go back.''
</P>
<P>
   Though prospects are bleak in Afghanistan, a drought in southern
Pakistan and declining assistance for refugees has encouraged some
to return.
</P>
<P>
   But many more wish to stay in Pakistan. Some pleaded with Ogata
to provide additional help.
</P>
<P>
   Abdul Rahim, a leader among the refugees, told Ogata that
children in the camps lacked basic needs such as health care and
schools.
</P>
<P>
   ''Like all people, we want to go home, but we can't right now,''
said Rahim. ''If things improve in Afghanistan, we will not stay a
second longer.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-17-00 2252 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
