<HEADLINE> Explosion Reported In Belfast  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) -- An explosion shook Belfast's
Shankill Road at the heart of the city's Protestant community
before dawn Monday, police said.
</P>
<P>
   Police and army technical officers answered a report of a blast
just before 2 a.m. at the offices of the organization Loyalist
Prisoners' Aid.
</P>
<P>
   There were no reports of injuries, but the blast caused
''substantial damage to the offices,'' a Royal Ulster Constabulary
spokeswoman said.
</P>
<P>
   Loyalist Prisoners' Aid represents former prisoners linked to
the Ulster Defense Association, a pro-British paramilitary group.
</P>
<P>
   A violent feud between the UDA and the rival Ulster Volunteer
Force has been blamed for three deaths, the shooting of an
11-year-old girl and a number of beatings and attacks on homes in
the last month. Some 170 families have been forced from their homes
in the Shankill area.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, a seniors home was evacuated while army bomb-disposal
experts defused an improvised bomb in the Shankill area, police
said.
</P>
