<HEADLINE> Netherlands 5, Australia 4  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia (AP) -- The Netherlands finally played like a
world power, scoring twice in the fourth quarter to rally past
Australia 5-4 in women's water polo at the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   The Dutch had gotten a medal in every major women's water polo
since 1979, but hadn't done much here -- except a lackluster, 8-6
win over Kazakstan, considered the only team of the six not in the
medals hunt.
</P>
<P>
   But trailing 4-3 at the start of the final period, the
Netherlands got going.
</P>
<P>
   Karin Kuipers swam in alone and tied things at 4. About 30
seconds later, Ellen van Der Weijden-Bast leaped high to tip in a
pass from Edmee Heimstra for the winning goal.
</P>
<P>
   The Australians, the only team to win their first two games, had
several chances to tie. Goalie Karla Plugge halted a charge by
Australian Naomi Castle. Bridgette Gusterson, the Aussie's leading
scorer, skipped a close shot into the chest of Marjan Op den Velde.
</P>
<P>
   Simone Hankin missed a desperation backhand shot for Australia's
last chance.
</P>
<P>
   The Dutch and Australia both are 2-1. Four of the six teams will
advance to Saturday's medals round.
</P>
<P>
   The Australian's take on the United States on Tuesday (Monday
night EDT). The Netherlands will face Canada on Tuesday night
(Tuesday morning EDT).
</P>
</TEXT>
