<HEADLINE> TV Personality Paula Yates Dies  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- TV personality Paula Yates, girlfriend of the late
INXS singer Michael Hutchence, was found dead at her London home on
Sunday, police said. She was 40.
</P>
<P>
   Scotland Yard said the cause of death was not immediately known,
and that an autopsy would be scheduled. Detective Inspector Mike
Christensen said there were no signs of violence in the house.
</P>
<P>
   He said the body was discovered by a family friend, and an
ambulance and police were called to the scene.
</P>
<P>
   Yates was Hutchence's partner from 1994 until November 1997,
when he committed suicide by hanging himself in a hotel room in
Sydney, Australia. She had a daughter with him in 1996, Heavenly
Hiraani Tiger Lily.
</P>
<P>
   News reports in Britain had said Yates was treated for
depression after Hutchence's death.
</P>
<P>
   In Sydney, Hutchence's father was reported to be ''absolutely
shocked and saddened'' by Yates' death.
</P>
<P>
   Kell Hutchence's wife, Susie Hutchence, said her husband was
''very distressed and very upset.''
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, the surviving members of INXS said: ''Our
thoughts and love are with Tiger and Paula's family.''
</P>
<P>
   Yates was also the former wife of pop musician Bob Geldof, with
whom she had three children.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are all so sad,'' Geldof said in a statement. ''The loss
for all the children is insupportable.''
</P>
<P>
   Yates was a co-presenter in the 1980s on the music show ''The
Tube.'' She also had appeared on ''The Big Breakfast,'' an offbeat
morning program where she interviewed celebrity guests on a giant
bed.
</P>
</TEXT>
