<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-17 23:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Romanian Folk Singer Dies at 47  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUCHAREST, Romania (AP) -- Valeriu Stelian, a folk singer who
inspired anti-communist protesters a decade ago, has died of
cancer, a family friend said Sunday. He was 47.
</P>
<P>
   Valeriu Stelian died at Bucharest's Fundeni hospital Saturday,
one week after undergoing surgery for cancer, said Sorin Minghiat,
Stelian's flute player.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after the 1989 anti-communist uprising, Stelian went
with his guitar to University Square, in downtown Bucharest. There
he sang and played to students who had gathered to protest the
presence of former communists in government, even after the bloody
1989 revolt.
</P>
<P>
   Six weeks later, coal miners descended on Bucharest at the
behest of the government and beat up the students. Six people died
in the melee and the protest harmed Romania's image to such a
degree that many young Romanians emigrated, believing democracy
would never come to this Balkan country.
</P>
<P>
   ''Oh God, come here to see what has become of people,'' went the
lyrics of one of Stelian's songs composed in 1973 and played to
film footage of people who had died during the 1989 anti-communist
uprising.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Stelian made the headlines again after he was
involved in a car accident where three people died. Charges against
him were dropped, but he was badly affected by the incident,
friends said.
</P>
<P>
   During his career, Stelian toured the former Soviet Union,
Norway, Poland, Bulgaria, Hungary, France, England and the United
States. He also set up some recording studios in Romania in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   The singer is survived by a wife and child. Funeral plans were
not immediately known.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
