<DOCNO> APW20000917.0161 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-17 23:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 49ers Makes Splash in Olympic Debut  </HEADLINE>
By BERNIE WILSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia (AP) -- One after another, the flag-emblazoned
spinnakers popped open as they caught the breeze, propelling a
fleet of 49ers downwind on Sydney Harbor.
</P>
<P>
   You didn't need a program to figure out where the crews were
from. A Union Jack flew open, followed by the flags of Ukraine,
Poland, Australia and then the Stars and Stripes of the boat crewed
by brothers Jonathan and Charlie McKee of Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   The 49er made a colorful Olympic debut on Monday (Sunday night
EDT), even if the first of three scheduled races was skewed by a
180-degree wind shift.
</P>
<P>
   The McKees finished sixth in the first race in the fleet of 17.
</P>
<P>
   The high-performance 49er -- it's named after its length, 4.99
meters -- was designed four years ago along the lines of the famous
Sydney 18-footer.
</P>
<P>
   The Olympic 49ers are made more visible with their flag
spinnakers.
</P>
<P>
   The 49ers weren't at their wildest because the wind was only
about 6 knots, with gusts to 9 knots. When the wind blows, these
winged skiffs can really move, sometimes reaching 25 knots. The
crew, held by safety lines, prop themselves out over the water to
try to keep the boat level.
</P>
<P>
   The McKees, who each own an Olympic medal, say they wouldn't be
here if not for the wild-and-wooly 49er. Jonathan, 40, won a gold
in the Flying Dutchman in 1984 and Charlie, 38, a bronze in the 470
in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   The McKees sail the 49er because it keeps them on the edge, and
that's what organizers hope spectators will get to see over the
course of 16 races.
</P>
<P>
   On the first leg into the wind, a green and yellow ferry steamed
past on its way to Manly, with passengers packed along the rail,
getting a free glimpse of the action.
</P>
<P>
   The British skiff opened a huge lead on the upwind first leg,
and held it until getting caught in a wind hole halfway through the
race. The breeze, which had started from the southwest, suddenly
came out of the northeast. That's an indication of how crazy it can
be sailing on the harbor.
</P>
<P>
   The McKees made out OK because they were in the middle of the
course when the wind shifted. The first race was won by reigning
world champion Santiago Lopez-Vazquez of Spain.
</P>
<P>
   Three other classes scheduled to race Monday, the Soling,
Tornado and windsurfers, were delayed by lack of wind on their
courses, but finally got under way toward mid-afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Getting an Olympic windsurfing medal in Australia would be
especially fitting for American Lanee Butler.
</P>
<P>
   Butler, from Aliso Viejo, Calif., has lived and trained in
Sydney on and off since the 1996 Olympics, when she finished 11th.
She has an Aussie boyfriend and plans to live here for good after
these games, her third for the United States.
</P>
<P>
   She's going to have to rally a bit, though. She was in fourth
place after finishing second and fourth in the first two races
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   However, she was disqualified from the first race after a
protest by the Hong Kong sailor. The jury ruled that Butler failed
to keep clear of the Hong Kong board, leading to a collision.
</P>
<P>
   That dropped her to 16th overall. Although each sailor discards
his or her two worst scores after nine races, Butler's
disqualification gives her a little less room for error.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Tornado crew of John Lovell of New Orleans and Charlie
Ogletree of Newport Beach, Calif., finished fifth in the first of
two races to improve to fifth overall.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-17-00 2346 </TRAILER>
